**BREAKING CHANGE**, all api methods now use the (err, content) convention

It means that instead of doing:

``` js
  index.search(function found(success, content) {
    if (!success) {
      console.log('Error was:', content);
      return;
    }

    console.log('OK!', content);
  });
```

You must do:

``` js
  index.search(function found(err, content) {
    if (err) {
      console.log('Error was:', err);
      return;
    }

    console.log('OK!', content);
  });
```

This is in par with most asynchronous APIS accepted/de facto conventions.
It helps being compatible with control flow libraries like `async` and
helps reduce WTF moments of Node.JS developers used to cb(err, content)

fixes #42

Previously, it was usually an async callback but became synchronous
when the result was cached in this.cache. This violates best practice
that callbacks should either be always-sync or always-async.

For an oft-cited source of the idea that callbacks should either be consistently sync or consistently async, see http://blog.izs.me/post/59142742143/designing-apis-for-asynchrony. For a concrete example of how this inconsistent behaviour can be harmful in the case of this library, consider the code below (which is roughly equivalent to a real bug I had to figure out recently in some code that was using Algolia):

``` js
var searchHelper = new AlgoliaSearchHelper( ... );

// ...

$searchBox.change(function () {
    searchHelper.search(
        $searchBox.val(),
        function successHandler () {
            hideLoadingSpinner();
            // ...
            // (some other stuff)
        }
    );
    showLoadingSpinner();
})
```

The subtle bug my colleague created here (that if you search for something you've searched for already, the callback fires _before_ the change handler returns and so the loading spinner never disappears) seems like a trap that others are likely to fall into as well, and it would not be possible with the change I've suggested in this commit, since the callback now _always_ happens asynchronously.
